      <section id="what-a-geo-checker-does">
        <h2 class="anchor-top">What a GEO Checker Does</h2>
        <p><strong>A GEO checker produces a point-in-time assessment of your brand's presence in AI-generated answers — the starting line for any generative engine optimisation programme.</strong> It answers a fundamental question that traditional SEO tools cannot: when people ask AI platforms about topics in your category, does your brand appear in the response?</p>
        <p>The distinction between a <em>checker</em> and a <em>tracker</em> is important. A GEO checker is used for an initial audit or periodic snapshot — it measures where you stand today. A <a href="/geo-tracking-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO tracking tool</a> runs continuously, recording changes over time and alerting you to shifts in citation frequency. Both are part of a complete <a href="/geo-monitoring/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO monitoring</a> setup, but the checker comes first.</p>
        <p>At its core, a GEO checker works by querying AI platforms with prompts that reflect the questions your target customers are likely to ask — and then recording whether, how, and where your brand appears in the generated responses. This can be done manually using the platforms' own interfaces, or with dedicated software that automates the query process and aggregates results across platforms.</p>
        <p>The output of a GEO check is not a single score or rank. It is a structured picture: your citation frequency for a defined query set, broken down by platform, with notes on which URLs were cited, how your brand was described, and where competitors appeared instead. This baseline is what makes <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> work measurable — you cannot demonstrate progress without knowing your starting point.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="how-to-check-manually">
        <h2 class="anchor-top">How to Check Your AI Visibility Manually</h2>
        <p><strong>A manual GEO check is free, requires no specialist tools, and can be completed in under two hours — making it the right starting point for any brand assessing its AI visibility for the first time.</strong></p>
        <p>Follow these steps to run a structured manual check:</p>

        <ol class="mt-6 space-y-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed list-decimal list-outside pl-5">
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink-100">Build your query list.</strong> Write twenty to thirty prompts that reflect how your target audience searches for solutions in your category. Include informational queries ("what is the best [category] for [use case]"), comparison queries ("compare [your brand] vs [competitor]"), and recommendation queries ("which [product/service] should I use for [problem]"). Vary phrasing — "what", "how", "recommend", "which" — because AI responses are sensitive to query framing.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink-100">Select your platforms.</strong> At minimum, test ChatGPT (GPT-4o), Perplexity, Google Gemini, and Microsoft Copilot. Add Google AI Overviews if organic search is an important channel for your audience. Log in to each platform so your results reflect the default experience, not a guest or restricted mode.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink-100">Run each query and record results.</strong> Use a simple spreadsheet with columns for: platform, query, brand present (yes/no), cited URL, description of brand (if present), competitors mentioned, and any notes. Run each query fresh — do not copy from a previous session that might carry conversational context.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink-100">Calculate your citation frequency.</strong> For each platform, divide the number of queries where your brand appeared by the total number of queries run. A 20% citation frequency on Perplexity means your brand appeared in 4 of 20 sampled queries. Compare this across platforms to identify where your biggest gaps are.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink-100">Note competitor patterns.</strong> Record which competitors appear in queries where you do not. Consistent competitor presence for specific query types is a signal that their content structure, entity data, or backlink profile is better aligned to what those platforms retrieve.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink-100">Document your baseline.</strong> Save your spreadsheet with a date stamp. This is your GEO baseline — the reference point against which all future checks and improvements will be measured.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <div class="mt-8 rounded-xl border border-[var(--line)] bg-[rgba(var(--accent-glow),.04)] p-6">
          <p class="font-semibold text-ink-100 mb-2">Manual check limitations</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">AI responses are probabilistic — the same query can produce different results on successive runs. A manual check based on a single run per query will contain sampling error. For greater accuracy, run each query three times and record whether your brand appeared in at least two of the three responses. For ongoing monitoring at scale, manual checking is impractical; this is where <a href="/geo-tracking-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">dedicated tracking tools</a> become necessary.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="what-to-look-for">
        <h2 class="anchor-top">What to Look for When Checking Your GEO Visibility</h2>
        <p><strong>Six signals determine the diagnostic value of a GEO check — recording all six turns a raw pass/fail presence check into an actionable audit.</strong> Use these as the columns in your manual checking spreadsheet, or as the criteria against which to evaluate what a GEO checker tool reports.</p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-8 rounded-xl border border-[var(--line)]">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead class="bg-[rgba(var(--accent-glow),.06)]">
              <tr>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold text-ink-100">Signal</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold text-ink-100">What to record</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold text-ink-100">Why it matters</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
              {checkSignals.map((row, i) => (
                <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? '' : 'bg-[rgba(255,255,255,.01)]'}>
                  <td class="px-5 py-4 font-medium text-ink-100 whitespace-nowrap">{row.signal}</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-4 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">{row.whatToLook}</td>
                  <td class="px-5 py-4 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">{row.whyItMatters}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-6 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Of these six signals, <strong>cited URL</strong> and <strong>description accuracy</strong> are the most actionable. If you know which of your pages are being cited, you know where to invest in structural improvements. If you know your brand is described inaccurately or inconsistently, you have a clear entity data task — updating Wikipedia, Wikidata, structured data markup, and authoritative third-party sources to establish a consistent, accurate knowledge graph presence.</p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Platform variation is the signal most often overlooked. Significant differences in your citation rate between Perplexity and ChatGPT, for example, can indicate that one platform's retrieval system is more aligned to your content's current structure. Understanding <a href="/how-to-measure-geo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">how to measure GEO</a> performance across platforms is a prerequisite for deciding where to prioritise optimisation effort.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="checker-tools">
        <h2 class="anchor-top">GEO Checker Tools: What to Look For</h2>
        <p><strong>Dedicated GEO checker tools automate the manual process, run queries across multiple platforms simultaneously, and produce structured reports that a spreadsheet cannot match at scale.</strong> The category is evolving rapidly, so rather than publishing a fixed ranked list, this section describes the characteristics that distinguish a genuinely useful tool from a superficial one.</p>

        <p class="mt-4 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">The best GEO checker tools share five characteristics. First, they allow you to input your own query list rather than relying on vendor-defined templates. Generic prompts will not reflect your specific business context. Second, they cover all four major platforms as a minimum (ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, Copilot) and run queries against each simultaneously. Third, they return the full response text or a summary — not just a binary present/absent flag — so you can assess description accuracy and response position. Fourth, they identify which specific URL was cited, not just whether a domain appeared. Fifth, they allow you to benchmark against named competitors by running the same query set for them.</p>

        <p class="mt-4 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Publicly known platforms that have offered AI visibility checking functionality include <strong>Profound</strong>, <strong>Otterly.ai</strong>, <strong>Peec AI</strong>, and <strong>Semrush's AI Toolkit</strong>. Some of these operate primarily as ongoing trackers with a checker capability built in; others offer standalone audit modes. The landscape changes frequently — always verify current features and pricing directly with vendors before committing. See the broader <a href="/geo-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO tools guide</a> for a framework for evaluating the full tool ecosystem.</p>

        <div class="mt-8 rounded-xl border border-[var(--line)] bg-[rgba(var(--accent-glow),.04)] p-6">
          <p class="font-semibold text-ink-100 mb-2">Note on tool accuracy</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">No GEO checker tool produces perfectly accurate results because AI platform responses are probabilistic. Any tool's citation frequency figures are statistical estimates, not exact counts. When evaluating a tool, ask the vendor how many response samples they collect per query and how they handle variation between runs. A credible tool is transparent about this; one that presents a single "visibility score" without explaining its derivation warrants caution.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="after-the-check">
        <h2 class="anchor-top">What to Do After Your GEO Check</h2>
        <p><strong>A GEO check that does not lead to action is an exercise in measurement for its own sake — the value is in using the results to prioritise optimisation work.</strong></p>
        <p>Start with the queries where competitors appear and you do not. Analyse the cited competitor pages: how are they structured? Do they use clear definitions, direct answers, structured lists, or FAQ sections? Are they referenced from authoritative third-party sources? These are the structural patterns that retrieval systems favour, and they point directly to the improvements your own content needs.</p>
        <p>If your brand appears in responses but is described inaccurately, prioritise entity work: review and update your Wikipedia article, Wikidata entry, and the authoritative third-party sources that AI models draw on when building factual claims. Structured data markup (Schema.org Organisation and WebSite) on your own site also contributes to entity recognition.</p>
        <p>If you are present on some platforms but absent on others, study the difference. Perplexity, for example, relies heavily on live web retrieval and tends to favour pages that are well-structured, recently updated, and cited by authoritative sources. ChatGPT without browsing draws more heavily on training data, making entity presence in knowledge bases and long-standing authoritative content more influential.</p>
        <p>Once you have completed your initial check and identified priority actions, the next step is to move from periodic checking to continuous monitoring. A <a href="/geo-tracking-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO tracking tool</a> will measure the impact of your optimisation work over time and alert you to unexpected changes — giving you the data needed to demonstrate ROI and guide the next iteration of your programme. See our <a href="/geo-monitoring/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO monitoring hub</a> for the full picture of how checking and tracking work together.</p>
      </section>

    </article>
  </div>

